1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:05,673
You're listening to: Building Scalable Microservices with Go and FastAPI.

2
00:00:05,673 --> 00:00:17,560
How I learned to combine Go and Python microservices the hard way - after our monolith crashed during peak hours at Dr. Dangs Lab. Real patterns from processing millions of healthcare transactions.

3
00:00:17,560 --> 00:00:18,605
Let's get started.

4
00:00:18,605 --> 00:00:21,730
Now, let's talk about The Day Our Monolith Died.

5
00:00:21,730 --> 00:00:24,603
It was 9:47 AM on a Monday.

6
00:00:24,603 --> 00:00:28,389
Our lab management system at Dr. Dangs Lab had just crashed.

7
00:00:28,389 --> 00:00:35,576
200+ patients were waiting for their reports, 80 doctors couldn't access test results, and my phone wouldn't stop buzzing.

8
00:00:35,576 --> 00:00:36,466
The culprit?

9
00:00:36,466 --> 00:00:43,713
Our Python monolith was trying to process 500 lab reports simultaneously while handling API requests.

10
00:00:43,713 --> 00:00:48,725
CPU hit 100%, memory exhausted, and the whole thing came down.

11
00:00:48,725 --> 00:00:56,334
That day taught me why microservices exist - not as a trendy architecture choice, but as a survival mechanism.

12
00:00:56,334 --> 00:01:00,492
Moving on to Why I Ended Up Using Both Go and FastAPI.

13
00:01:00,492 --> 00:01:04,531
After the crash, I spent two weeks analyzing our workloads.

14
00:01:04,531 --> 00:01:05,745
Here's what I found:

15
00:01:05,745 --> 00:01:13,329
CPU-bound work (report processing, PDF generation): Python was spending 80% of time waiting for GIL locks.

16
00:01:13,329 --> 00:01:17,295
Processing 100 reports took 45 seconds.

17
00:01:17,295 --> 00:01:19,963
Memory usage spiked unpredictably.

18
00:01:19,963 --> 00:01:27,307
I/O-bound work (API requests, database queries): Most requests were waiting on database/network.

19
00:01:27,307 --> 00:01:29,915
Python's async was actually fine here.

20
00:01:29,915 --> 00:01:33,076
Developer velocity mattered more than raw speed.

21
00:01:33,076 --> 00:01:38,064
The answer became obvious: Go for the heavy lifting, Python for everything else.

22
00:01:38,064 --> 00:01:40,312
The Performance Difference Was Shocking.

23
00:01:40,312 --> 00:01:43,834
I rewrote our report processor in Go as an experiment:

24
00:01:43,834 --> 00:01:48,581
Results: 100 reports: 45 seconds → 3 seconds.

25
00:01:48,581 --> 00:01:57,415
Memory: 2GB spikes → stable 200MB. CPU: 100% single core → distributed across 8 cores.

26
00:01:57,415 --> 00:01:58,497
I was sold.

27
00:01:58,497 --> 00:02:06,153
But I wasn't about to rewrite our entire API layer in Go - that would take months and our team knew Python inside out.

28
00:02:06,153 --> 00:02:08,713
Next up: Our Hybrid Architecture.

29
00:02:08,713 --> 00:02:10,216
Here's what we actually built:

30
00:02:10,216 --> 00:02:13,100
FastAPI Handles the API Layer.

31
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:16,742
I kept all patient-facing APIs in FastAPI.

32
00:02:16,742 --> 00:02:17,403
Why?

33
00:02:17,403 --> 00:02:20,516
Because I could ship features in hours, not days:

34
00:02:20,516 --> 00:02:22,608
Go Handles the Heavy Processing.

35
00:02:22,608 --> 00:02:27,536
When a batch of lab results comes in, FastAPI hands it off to our Go service:

36
00:02:27,536 --> 00:02:31,490
Let's explore The Communication Problem (And How I Almost Got It Wrong).

37
00:02:31,490 --> 00:02:35,240
My first attempt at connecting the services was... embarrassing.

38
00:02:35,240 --> 00:02:38,004
What Actually Works: Batch + Async.

39
00:02:38,004 --> 00:02:40,552
For Real-Time Stuff: gRPC.

40
00:02:40,552 --> 00:02:47,704
When we needed real-time status updates (doctors waiting for urgent results), HTTP polling was too slow.

41
00:02:47,704 --> 00:02:50,216
gRPC streaming solved it:

42
00:02:50,216 --> 00:02:56,117
The streaming version meant doctors saw results appearing in real-time instead of waiting for the whole batch.

43
00:02:56,117 --> 00:02:58,461
For Decoupled Work: Kafka.

44
00:02:58,461 --> 00:03:01,093
Some things don't need immediate responses.

45
00:03:01,093 --> 00:03:05,120
When a report is finalized, multiple systems need to know:

46
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:07,872
Now let's look at The Distributed Transaction Nightmare.

47
00:03:07,872 --> 00:03:10,204
Here's a scenario that kept me up at night:

48
00:03:10,204 --> 00:03:12,031
Patient pays for a test.

49
00:03:12,031 --> 00:03:13,521
Sample is collected.

50
00:03:13,521 --> 00:03:17,175
Payment fails (card declined after initial auth).

51
00:03:17,175 --> 00:03:18,978
Sample is already in the lab.

52
00:03:18,978 --> 00:03:19,326
???.

53
00:03:19,326 --> 00:03:22,776
In a monolith, you'd wrap it in a database transaction.

54
00:03:22,776 --> 00:03:25,360
With microservices, that's not possible.

55
00:03:25,360 --> 00:03:27,319
The Saga Pattern Saved Us.

56
00:03:27,319 --> 00:03:30,925
Now, let's talk about Deployment: What Actually Runs in Production.

57
00:03:30,925 --> 00:03:34,627
After getting burned by "it works on my machine" too many times:

58
00:03:34,627 --> 00:03:38,329
Moving on to Monitoring: Because You Can't Fix What You Can't See.

59
00:03:38,329 --> 00:03:44,038
After our third "silent failure" incident, I made observability non-negotiable:

60
00:03:44,038 --> 00:03:46,237
Next up: What I'd Do Differently.

61
00:03:46,237 --> 00:03:49,687
Looking back after 2 years of running this in production:

62
00:03:49,687 --> 00:03:53,557
Start with a monolith - We extracted services too early.

63
00:03:53,557 --> 00:03:55,865
Should have waited for clear pain points..

64
00:03:55,865 --> 00:04:04,086
Shared database was fine initially - The "each service owns its data" rule caused more problems than it solved for our team size..

65
00:04:04,086 --> 00:04:13,100
gRPC from day one - HTTP was easier to start but we eventually rewrote all internal communication to gRPC anyway..

66
00:04:13,100 --> 00:04:20,600
Invest in local dev environment - Running 5 services locally was painful until we set up docker-compose properly..

67
00:04:20,600 --> 00:04:24,026
Contract testing - Integration tests were flaky.

68
00:04:24,026 --> 00:04:28,737
Consumer-driven contract tests (Pact) would have saved hours of debugging..

69
00:04:28,737 --> 00:04:30,456
Let's explore The Results.

70
00:04:30,456 --> 00:04:32,163
After 18 months:

71
00:04:32,162 --> 00:04:35,237
Metric, Monolith, Microservices.

72
00:04:35,237 --> 00:04:40,982
Report processing, 45s/batch, 3s/batch.

73
00:04:40,982 --> 00:04:47,280
API latency p99, 2.1s, 180ms.

74
00:04:47,280 --> 00:04:50,237
Deployment frequency, Weekly, Daily.

75
00:04:50,237 --> 00:04:54,251
Incidents/month, 4-5, 0-1.

76
00:04:54,251 --> 00:04:58,902
Time to add new feature, 2-3 days, 4-6 hours.

77
00:04:58,902 --> 00:04:59,816
Was it worth it?

78
00:04:59,816 --> 00:05:00,898
Absolutely.

79
00:05:00,898 --> 00:05:03,494
But I wouldn't recommend it for every project.

80
00:05:03,494 --> 00:05:06,378
We needed it because our scale demanded it.

81
00:05:06,378 --> 00:05:07,845
Now let's look at Wrapping Up.

82
00:05:07,845 --> 00:05:16,703
The combination of Go for performance-critical paths and FastAPI for rapid API development has worked incredibly well for us.

83
00:05:16,703 --> 00:05:19,984
But the real lesson isn't about languages - it's about:

84
00:05:19,984 --> 00:05:23,362
Understanding your actual bottlenecks before optimizing.

85
00:05:23,362 --> 00:05:25,970
Keeping services focused and small.

86
00:05:25,970 --> 00:05:28,530
Investing heavily in observability.

87
00:05:28,530 --> 00:05:32,292
Accepting that distributed systems are inherently complex.

88
00:05:32,292 --> 00:05:39,708
If you're considering microservices, ask yourself: do you actually need them, or is your monolith just poorly structured?

89
00:05:39,708 --> 00:05:43,193
Often, a well-organized monolith is the right answer.

90
00:05:43,193 --> 00:05:45,068
Got questions about this architecture?

91
00:05:45,068 --> 00:05:51,246
I've made plenty of mistakes not covered here - feel free to reach out on LinkedIn or check out more of my work on GitHub.

92
00:05:51,246 --> 00:05:53,037
And that's the end of this article.

93
00:05:53,037 --> 00:05:54,179
Thanks for listening.

